	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>6502-based LCD watch idea</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hi, folks.  I'll just explain a daydream I was having yesterday:<br /><br />I was shopping around for a new/used watch and still love the retro aesthetic of old Casio databank watches.  I'd love a programmable one, like the old Seiko/Epson UC ones ( <a href="https://www.google.com/search?safe=off&amp;q=seiko+uc-2200" class="postlink">link</a> ) but those are getting really rare and expensive.<br /><br />Smartwatches are cool, but bulky as hell and have a horrible battery life.<br /><br />DIY watches are even larger &amp; usually LED &amp; push-button to view.<br /><br />I know that there are embedded 6502 cores in tiny devices like Tamagotchis &amp; photo keychains, so wouldn't it be cool to have such a core + RTC chip + dot-matrix LCD interface to an existing watch (like a Casio <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=casio+databank+LCD&amp;safe=off" class="postlink">databank</a> ) + UART interface for ASM program uploading?<br /><br />Coincidentally, I just discovered 2 such ideas, but using watches &amp; chips that I find less interesting due to limited display and more HLL programming:<br /><br /><a href="https://goodwatch.org/posts/introducing-the-goodwatch/" class="postlink">https://goodwatch.org/posts/introducing-the-goodwatch/</a> Very cool...<br /><a href="https://github.com/carrotIndustries/pluto" class="postlink">https://github.com/carrotIndustries/pluto</a> Neat, but more limited.<br /><a href="http://www.eevblog.com/forum/oshw/diy-watch-based-on-the-casio-f-91w/" class="postlink">http://www.eevblog.com/forum/oshw/diy-watch-based-on-the-casio-f-91w/</a><br /><br />Anyway, is the embedded 6502 watch idea silly, feasible, etc.?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


